WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Hey econ students, this is Jacob Clifford.
I made this video for one reason: to save

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
you time in an economics class. Your
teacher or professors can expect you to be able

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
to use supply and demand — not just know
supply and demand. So I made this video

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
to bridge that gap between introduction
and application as fast as possible.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Now do me a favor — don't take any notes
as you watch this video the first time

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
through. Just understand the concepts, and
then later if you need to, come back and

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
take notes. So here we go — everything you
need to know about supply and demand in

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
less than eight minutes. Okay, let's start
off with demand. This is a demand curve

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
and it shows the inverse relationship
between price and the quantity that

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
consumers are willing and able to buy. So
the quantity demanded — when the price

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
goes up, the quantity demanded falls, and the
price goes down, the quantity demanded

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
increases and people want to buy more.
There are three reasons for the law of demand.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
The first one is the substitution effect.
When the price goes up for ice cream,

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
people substitute away from ice cream
and go buy other products like candy bars.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And if the price falls for ice cream,
people substitute away from candy bars

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
and start buying more ice cream. The
second reason is the income effect. When

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.000
the price goes up for ice cream, people
are going to buy less ice cream because

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
they have less purchasing power. They can
buy less ice cream. And when the price

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
falls for ice cream, the quantity demanded is
going to increase because people can buy

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.000
more ice cream — each dollar buys more ice
cream than before. The third reason is

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
the law of diminishing marginal utility.
As you consume more and more ice cream,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
you get less and less additional
satisfaction or happiness from it. So the

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
price has to fall to increase the
quantity that people are going to buy. So

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
if you already bought one ice cream cone,
to get you to buy another one they've

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
got to lower the price. That shows you an
inverse relationship between price and

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.000
quantity — the law of demand. Now
notice: when there's a change in the

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
price, that moves along the demand curve.
But what if something else changes that

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
causes the demand curve to shift? There are
five shifters or determinants of demand

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
that cause the demand curve to increase
and shift to the right, or decrease and

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
shift to the left. The first one is taste
and preferences. For example, if it's 100

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
degrees outside, then the demand for ice
cream would shift to the right. But

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
notice we're not talking about a change
in the price of ice cream. The price is

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
staying the same. It's some other factor
that's causing demand to go up — people

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.000
are buying more because it's a hot day
outside. And if it was a cold day outside,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
at every single price people would buy
less because they don't want to buy ice

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
cream because it's freezing. The second shifter is
more consumers — more consumers would

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
increase demand, less consumers or fewer
buyers would decrease demand. The third

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
shifter is the price of substitutes and
complements. Notice this is not the price

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
of ice cream — this is the price of some
other good, like candy bars. Candy bar is

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
an ice cream substitute. So if the
price goes up for candy bars, people can

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
buy more ice cream and the demand curve
is going to shift to the right. But ice

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
cream and ice cream cones are not
substitutes — they're complements. So if

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
the price goes up for cones, that's going
to cause the demand to go down for ice

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
cream. Again, we're talking about the
price changing, but not the price of ice

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
cream — the price of some different
product that's related to ice cream. The

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
next shifter is income, and it depends on
the type of product because there are

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
normal goods and inferior goods. A
normal good is when income goes up,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
people buy more of it. When income goes
down, people buy less of it. But an inferior

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:59.000
good is when income goes up, people
actually buy less of that product, and

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
when income goes down, people would buy
more. Ice cream is probably a normal good,

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
but Top Ramen is an example of an
inferior good — when incomes go down,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
people actually end up buying more of it.
The fifth and final shifter of demand is

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
a change in expectations. So if you
expect prices to go up in the future,

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
maybe the demand will increase now. So
there we go — those are the five shifters

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
of demand. And notice the price of ice cream
is not on that list. Price moves along

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.000
the curve — these shift the curve. Okay,
let's keep going. Now let's switch over to supply.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
This is a supply curve. It shows a positive
relationship between price and the

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
quantity supplied. The reason for this
has to do with making profit. If the

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
price is low for ice cream, producers
don't want to produce very much because

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
they're not going to make very much
money. If the price goes up, they're going

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.000
to want to produce a whole lot more
because they're going to make more

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
profit. So again, a change in the price of
ice cream moves along the supply curve.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:55.000
But there are also five shifters of supply.
The first one is a change in the price

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
of resources or inputs to produce ice
cream. For example, the price of milk goes

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
up — that's going to cause the supply to
decrease. Now notice here a decrease in

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
supply is a shift to the left. So just
like demand, an increase is to the right,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
a decrease is to the left. Now if the price were
to fall for some resource of producing

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
ice cream, then the supply would shift to
the right and that would be an increase.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
The second shifter of supply is a change
in technology. So if there's a new

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
machine that produces ice cream faster
and cheaper, that would cause the supply

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
curve to shift to the right. The third
shifter is some sort of action by the

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
government — subsidies, taxes, or some
sort of regulation. So a tax on ice cream

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.000
producers would cause the supply
to decrease and shift to the left. A subsidy —

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
if the government gave them more money
to produce more — that would shift it to

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
the right. And some sort of regulation, like
limiting the amount of ice cream we

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
could produce, would decrease the supply.
The fourth shifter of supply is number

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
of sellers. So if there are fewer sellers,
supply would shift to the left. If

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
there are more sellers, there's more supply
and it shifts to the right. And the fifth

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
and final shifter of supply is a change
in expectations. If producers think the

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
price is going to go up for ice cream in
the future, maybe they'll hold back

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.000
supply now and wait to go sell it later.
Okay, there we go — those are the five

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
shifters or determinants of supply,
showing you why a supply curve might

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
shift to the right or left. But notice
the price of ice cream is not on that

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
list, because price does not shift the
curve. Price moves along the curve.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Now we finally have enough to put supply
and demand together. We've got a demand

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
curve — now here comes the supply curve —
and we can find equilibrium. Economists

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
call this the market clearing price. It's
the only price where the quantity demanded

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
equals the quantity supplied. And if
there's a change in the price for ice

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
cream, that moves along the demand and
the supply curve, changing the quantity

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
demanded and the quantity supplied. This
is called disequilibrium. For example, the

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
price is down here — the quantity demanded is
greater than the quantity supplied, and

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
that is a shortage. At this low price,
consumers want to buy a whole lot of ice

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
cream, but producers don't want to
produce very much, and there is a

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
shortage. But if the price goes up here,
the quantity supplied increases — producers want

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
to produce a lot, but at the high price
consumers don't want to buy very much.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
That means there's a surplus. But really,
in a free market there's no reason for

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
the price to stay up there. If prices are
too high, eventually producers are going to

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
start lowering the price and that'll put
us back at equilibrium. And if prices

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
were too low, then consumers would bid up
the price of those products until

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
eventually it reaches equilibrium. The
point is, unless the government is

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
involved in controlling prices, just
assume we're at equilibrium in a free

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
market. All right, now I'm excited. Now we
have supply and demand equilibrium — we

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
can start using that to find out what's
going to happen to price and quantity. Okay,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
here we go. We've got demand and supply
at equilibrium. Let's say there's a study

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
that comes out that says ice cream makes
you smarter. How is that going to affect

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
the price and the quantity of ice cream?
Well, people prefer to be smart, and that

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
means that's going to increase the
demand, shifting it to the right. So the

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
price and the quantity are going to
increase. But if some study said that ice

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
cream actually makes you dumber, that
would decrease demand, causing the price

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
and the quantity to fall. But what if
instead there was some machine that

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
could produce ice cream quicker and
cheaper? That would increase the supply

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
because it's affecting production — price
would go down, quantity would go up. But

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
if instead we ran out of milk and the
price of milk increased, then the supply

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
for ice cream would decrease, price would
go up, and quantity would go down. And

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
that's it. It seems like a lot, but there are
really only four things that can happen:

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
demand can go up, demand
can go down, supply can go up, or supply

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
can go down. And in each case the
equilibrium price and quantity changes.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
But you don't need to memorize it — just
draw the graph. When in doubt, draw it out.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
Okay, that's it for supply and demand.
There are several things I didn't cover —

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
for example, price controls: when the
government controls the price, ceilings

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
and floors, or double shifts. But I have
videos that cover those concepts. And if

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
you're in macroeconomics, you're going to
take what you learned about supply and

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
demand in a market and apply it to the
entire economy when you look at

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
aggregate demand and aggregate supply.
And if you're in a microeconomics class,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
you're going to learn about elasticity —
it looks at the shape of the supply and

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
the demand curve. The point here is
you've got the basics, but there's a lot

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
more stuff that you're going to have to
learn. And most importantly, you have to

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
sit down and actually practice. So don't
think just watching one video with me is

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
going to help you. You've got to sit down,
practice different scenarios of shifting

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
demand and supply. And of course, if you
need more help practicing, take a look at

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
my ultimate review packet. And if you're
a teacher, take a look at my economics

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
worksheets. Thank you so much for
watching my videos. Make sure to

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
subscribe. Until next time!
